author: Irina Anghel
description: A gauge of UK business confidence rose to a nine-month high, climbing back to a level not seen since soon after Prime Minister Keir Starmer first took power, as markets rebounded and trade tensions eased with the US.
title: UK Business Confidence Hits 9-Month High in Boost for Starmer

author: Hadriana Lowenkron
description: The US State Department has notified Congress that it will shut down the office that helped resettle Afghan refugees who assisted the American war effort, provoking an outcry from nonprofit groups that helped evacuate people when the Taliban retook control of the country in 2021.
title: State Department Plans to Close Office That Aids Afghan Refugees

author: Norah Mulinda
description: Federal Housing Finance Agency Director Bill Pulte said he cannot envision a situation where President Donald Trump relinquishes control of Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, emphasizing there is a need to keep implicit guarantees intact as the administration considers potential options for the two mortgage giants.
title: Pulte Sees No Scenario Where Trump Isn’t in Control of Fannie Mae, Freddie Mac

author: Michelle Kaske
description: New York Governor Kathy Hochul and New Jersey Governor Phil Murphy broke ground Thursday on a $10 billion redevelopment of Manhattan’s bus terminal, the busiest in the world.
title: Hochul and Murphy Break Ground on $10 Billion NYC Bus Terminal

author: Hatem Mohareb
description: Libya’s attorney general ordered the detention of three people accused of storming the state oil company’s headquarters after authorities in the country’s eastern half threatened to shut oil output in response to the episode.
title: Libya Detains Three in State Oil Attack to Defuse Supply Threat

author: Keith Naughton, Ari Natter
description: Ford Motor Co.’s plan to make electric-vehicle batteries at a new site in Michigan would be put at risk if Congress cuts federal incentives for clean energy, the company’s chair said.
title: Ford Says Michigan Battery Plant at Risk If Tax Credits Are Cut

author: Gregory Korte
description: The Trump administration is adding four essay questions to applications for civil service jobs, asking applicants about their favorite executive orders and their commitment to government efficiency.
title: Federal Job Seekers Will Be Quizzed on Trump’s Executive Orders

author: Daniel Flatley
description: This is Washington Edition, the newsletter about money, power and politics in the nation’s capital. Today, Treasury reporter Daniel Flatley looks at the legal battle over the legality of the president’s tariffs. Sign up here and follow us at @bpolitics. Email our editors here.
title: Trump Gets a Tariff Reprieve as Advisers Plot Out a Plan B

author: Ye Xie, Liz Capo McCormick
description: Buried deep in the more than 1,000-page tax-and-spending bill that President Donald Trump is muscling through Congress is an obscure tax measure that’s setting off alarms on Wall Street and beyond.
title: Obscure Tax Item in Trump’s Big Bill Stokes Wall Street Angst

author: Brett Pulley
description: A $157 million plan to turn an Atlanta highway overpass into a park and provide 3,000 housing units is in jeopardy from President Donald Trump and the Republican-controlled Congress, Mayor Andre Dickens said.
title: Atlanta’s $157 Million Highway Revamp at Risk From Trump Cuts

author: Erik Larson, Greg Stohr
description: A federal appeals court temporarily paused a ruling against President Donald Trump’s global tariffs while weighing a longer lasting hold on the sweeping decision, with the administration vowing to take the matter to the US Supreme Court if necessary.
title: Appeals Court Allows Trump Tariffs to Stay in Effect for Now

author: Joao Lima
description: Portugal’s center-right leader Luis Montenegro was formally named prime minister for a second term after his ruling coalition won a snap election earlier this month.
title: Portugal’s Montenegro Is Formally Named Premier for Second Term

author: Gabrielle Coppola
description: Hyundai Motor Co. is preparing to increase the price of all of its US vehicles as the automaker looks to cushion the blow from tariffs imposed by President Donald Trump, according to people familiar with the matter.
title: Hyundai Weighs Across-the-Board US Price Hikes to Blunt Tariffs

author: Carrington York
description: Off-price retailer Burlington Stores’ top executive sees an opportunity in the tumultuous tariff situation.
title: Burlington CEO Expects Tariff Turmoil to Help Discount Retailers

author: Ian King
description: Synopsys Inc., a top maker of chip-design software, suspended its financial guidance for the current quarter and fiscal year after receiving word from the US government about new restrictions on exports to China.
title: Synopsys Suspends Guidance After US Notice on Export Curbs

author: Philip Aldrick, Tom Rees, Irina Anghel
description: Bank of England Governor Andrew Bailey has urged the government to strike a deeper trade deal with the European Union to improve growth and “minimize negative effects” of Brexit.
title: BOE’s Bailey Urges Closer EU Trade to Reverse Brexit Damage

author: Erik Larson, Josh Wingrove, Shawn Donnan, Laura Curtis
description: The US Court of International Trade has blocked the vast majority of President Donald Trump’s tariffs, dealing a blow to a key pillar of his economic agenda.
title: What’s Next for Trump’s Trade War After Court Blocks Tariffs

author: Ailbhe Rea
description: We crossed a Rubicon today, in more ways than one. Keir Starmer said for the first time that British politics is now a straight fight between his Labour and Nigel Farage’s Reform, while Rachel Reeves has confirmed she will force large pension funds to back British assets if they do not do so voluntarily.
title: Starmer Takes on Farage, Reeves Takes on Pensions: Ailbhe Rea

author: Misha Savic
description: Russia accused Serbia of selling weaponry to Ukraine through third countries, potentially straining a relationship with a traditional ally that relies on Moscow for its energy supplies.
title: Russia Accuses Serbia of Backstabbing With Arms Sales to Ukraine

author: Josh Wingrove, Jennifer A Dlouhy
description: President Donald Trump’s appetite for new tariffs remains undeterred, even after a court hit his signature duties with their most devastating blow yet.
title: Trump Appeals on Tariffs While Mulling Other Ways to Impose

author: Erik Larson, Greg Stohr
description: The Trump administration said it would ask the US Supreme Court to intervene as soon as Friday if a federal appeals court doesn’t immediately put on hold a decision finding that most of the president’s tariffs are illegal.
title: US May Take Trump Tariff Case to Supreme Court on Friday

author: Thomas Gualtieri
description: Spain’s grid operator and the country’s largest utility took to public finger-wagging over their roles during the country’s biggest-ever blackout.
title: Spain Blackout Blame Game Heats Up as Iberdrola Points to Grid

author: David Voreacos
description: A federal judge weighing Harvard University’s lawsuit challenging the Trump administration’s ban on enrolling international students said she will expand a temporary block of its enforcement.
title: Harvard’s Reprieve From Foreign Student Ban Is Extended by Judge

author: Gregory Korte
description: Steve Davis, who served as Elon Musk’s de facto second-in-command at the Department of Government Efficiency, is following the billionaire adviser out of President Donald Trump’s signature cost-cutting effort, a person familiar with the move said Thursday.
title: Musk’s No. 2 Also Departing DOGE as Officials Hit Time Limit

author: Greg Ryan
description: Harvard University President Alan Garber played up the school’s international reach at its commencement ceremony as the institution battles the Trump administration over its right to enroll foreign students.
title: Harvard President Embraces Foreign Students at Commencement

author: Thomas Gualtieri
description: Spain’s three largest utilities are working on a proposal to extend the lifespan of the country’s biggest nuclear power plant, whose reactors are slated to be shut down in 2027 and 2028.
title: Spain’s Iberdrola, Endesa Aim to Extend Nuclear Plant Lifespan

author: Volodymyr Verbianyi
description: The International Monetary Fund reached a deal with Ukraine to disburse the next portion of a $15.5 billion loan package for the war-battered nation.
title: IMF Approves $500 Million Ukraine Payment as Peace Talks Stall

author: Yoshiaki Nohara
description: Japanese Prime Minister Shigeru Ishiba initiated a phone call with US President Donald Trump to discuss tariffs, and said the two deepened their understanding.
title: Ishiba Calls Trump to Talk Tariffs, Touts Deeper Understanding

author: Steven T. Dennis
description: Republican Senator Jim Banks and Democrat Elizabeth Warren are demanding answers from Nvidia Corp. CEO Jensen Huang on his firm’s reported plans to open a research facility in Shanghai, saying the decision “raises significant national security and economic security concerns.”
title: Nvidia Faces Bipartisan Concern on China Research Facility Plans

author: Lucy White
description: Reform UK leader Nigel Farage will attempt to woo younger British voters by announcing a Donald Trump-style foray into cryptocurrency policy at an Bitcoin conference in Las Vegas late on Thursday.
title: Reform’s Farage Sets Out Trump-Style Bid to Make UK a Crypto Hub

author: Krystof Chamonikolas
description: The Czech Republic’s most popular political party pledged to seek full state ownership in power producer CEZ AS to boost energy security if it returns to government after elections due in October.
title: Czech Election Frontrunners Prepare State Buyout of CEZ Utility

author: Colum Murphy
description: Just weeks after US President Donald Trump declared a “total reset” with China following a trade truce in Geneva, tensions are rising again between the world’s biggest economies.
title: Trump-Xi Truce Under Fire as US Targets Chinese Students, Tech

author: Joe Lovinger
description: Texas Republicans are tightening their grip on the state’s sprawling university systems amid a nationwide drive by conservatives to remake higher education.
title: Texas Follows Florida in Republican Push to Remake US Colleges

author: Antony Sguazzin
description: South African President Cyril Ramaphosa established a commission of inquiry to determine whether attempts were made to prevent the investigation and prosecution of apartheid-era crimes.
title: South Africa to Probe Delays in Prosecuting Apartheid Crimes

author: Akayla Gardner
description: National Economic Council Director Kevin Hassett said the administration is not yet pursuing alternative options for imposing sweeping tariffs a day after a court blocked some levies on imports in a stunning setback to President Donald Trump’s trade agenda.
title: Hassett Says US Has Other Options on Tariffs But Awaiting Appeal

author: Yian Lee, Miaojung Lin, Yvonne Man
description: Taiwan is continuing its efforts to secure a trade deal with the US, a top official said, even after a court blocked many of the tariffs that President Donald Trump has threatened to impose on other countries.
title: Taiwan Says US Trade-Deal Push Continues Despite Court Ruling

author: Hadriana Lowenkron, Jonathan Tirone
description: US President Donald Trump said he envisions a nuclear deal with Iran that would allow the destruction of “whatever we want” in the country including labs, a version of an inspections regime that is likely to be rejected by Tehran.
title: Trump Sees Iran Deal That Allows US to Destroy Nuclear Sites

author: Alberto Nardelli, Daryna Krasnolutska
description: Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskiy said China has stopped selling drones to Kyiv and other European nations while continuing shipments to Russia.
title: China Cut Drone Sales to West But Supplies Them to Russia, Ukraine Says

author: Thomas Kutty Abraham
description: Thai attorneys have dropped royal insult charges against a US academic citing a lack of evidence, almost two months after he was detained and stripped of his job at a local university.
title: Thai Attorneys Drop Royal Insult Charge Against US Academic

author: Francesca Stevens
description: A printed edition of The Economist magazine with Vietnam’s Communist Party General Secretary To Lam on the front cover has been blocked from distribution in the country, in the latest sign of the government’s tightening control over the media.
title: Vietnam Blocks Copies of The Economist Over To Lam Cover

author: Galit Altstein
description: Israel will build 22 new settlements in the West Bank including some along its eastern border with Jordan to strengthen its grip on the territory and block the establishment of an independent Palestinian state.
title: Israel Approves New Settlements to Obstruct Palestinian State

author: Ted Mann
description: The full effects of a drastic cost-cutting campaign are coming into focus as its billionaire architect departs from the government
title: Musk Exits DOGE Leaving Threadbare Agencies and Strained Workers

author: Alex Vasquez, Maya Averbuch
description: Welcome to Balance of Power, bringing you the latest in global politics. If you haven’t yet, sign up here.
title: Complex Mexican Vote May Be a Double-Edged Sword

author: S'thembile Cele, Ntando Thukwana
description: South Africa’s leftist Economic Freedom Fighters filed court papers in a bid to halt a proposed increase in fuel levies, the latest twist in a months-long tussle over the annual budget.
title: South Africa’s EFF Asks Court to Stop Proposed Fuel Levy Hike

author: Kim Chipman, Alicia Diaz, Erin Ailworth, Ilena Peng
description: After losing their biggest export market due to Donald Trump’s trade wars, US farmers are now counting on the president’s support for biofuels to prevent their next crop from piling up in storage.
title: Farmers Press Trump for Biofuels Boost to Counter Tariff Losses

author: Colum Murphy
description: China blasted the Trump administration’s move to revoke the visas of Chinese students in the US, underscoring the fragility of a recent steadying of ties between the world’s largest economies.
title: China Calls US Plan to Revoke Student Visas ‘Discriminatory’

author: Josh Xiao, Lucille Liu
description: China indicated it will not send its top military diplomat to a key defense forum in Asia for the first time since 2019, preventing a potential first encounter with US Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth.
title: China Defense Minister Skips Singapore Forum Attended by Hegseth

author: Salma El Wardany
description: Libya’s eastern government said it may shut down oil production and exports in protest after a militia aligned with rival authorities in the west stormed the state-oil company’s headquarters.
title: Libya Faces New Oil Shutdown Threat After Gunmen Storm HQ

author: Ditas B Lopez, Neil Jerome Morales
description: Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos Jr. promoted a police officer who led the arrest of his predecessor, Rodrigo Duterte, as part of a broader government reorganization following a setback in recent elections.
title: Marcos Promotes Police Officer Who Led Duterte Arrest

author: Shawn Donnan, Erik Larson, Laura Curtis
description: President Donald Trump’s tariff strategy has been thrown into turmoil after a US court issued a rare rebuke blocking many of the import taxes he has threatened and imposed on other countries.
title: Trump’s Trade Strategy Upended After Court Blocks Global Tariffs

author: Yoshiaki Nohara
description: Japan’s top trade negotiator Ryosei Akazawa is headed to Washington for his fourth round of trade negotiations with the US, signaling that talks will continue as expected despite a US court ruling that declared the tariffs illegal.
title: Japan’s Akazawa Heads to US for Latest Round of Tariff Talks

author: Selcuk Gokoluk, Wojciech Moskwa
description: Revved-up Polish markets will be put to the test this weekend as voters head to the polls in the biggest challenge facing Premier Donald Tusk.
title: Poland’s World-Beating Rally Is Facing an Election Reality Check

author: Swati Gupta
description: The ceasefire between India and Pakistan earlier this month was only achieved after US President Donald Trump offered the two countries trading access, Commerce Secretary Howard Lutnick said in a legal submission defending the White House’s tariff policy.
title: Lutnick Defends US Tariffs as Key to India-Pakistan Ceasefire

author: Brendan Scott
description: Keir Starmer is expected to hit back at what he described as Nigel Farage’s “fantasy economics,” in the latest sign that the Labour prime minister believes he must act to arrest Reform UK’s surge in opinion polls.
title: Starmer to Accuse Farage of Truss-Style ‘Fantasy’ Economic Plans

author: Chanyaporn Chanjaroen
description: Singapore Prime Minister Lawrence Wong told ruling party lawmakers to be vigilant in their interactions to avoid perceptions of impropriety.
title: Singapore Premier Warns Lawmakers on Perceptions of Impropriety

author: Laura Millan, Yinka Ibukun, Daniel Basteiro
description: The country is bucking European trends with its most ambitious migration push to date, including a proposal for a “mass regularization” of undocumented workers.
title: Spain Bets on 1 Million Migrants to Keep Its Economy Growing

author: Piotr Skolimowski, Wojciech Moskwa
description: Poland’s presidential election will determine whether the country can overhaul controversial judicial reforms and remain a reliable partner in the European Union after nearly a decade of divisive right-wing populism.
title: Why Poland’s Election Is a Barometer for Europe’s Populist Wave

author: Sabrina Willmer, Malathi Nayak
description: Delaware’s attorney general is planning to hire an investment bank that would advise her office as it examines OpenAI’s restructuring plans aimed at drawing more investors, according to a person familiar with the matter.
title: Delaware AG Seeking Bank to Advise on OpenAI Restructuring

author: Jason Gale
description: US Health and Human Services Secretary Robert F. Kennedy Jr. said he may bar government scientists from publishing in top medical journals, accusing publications like The New England Journal of Medicine of being “corrupt” and beholden to pharmaceutical companies.
title: RFK Jr. Slams Medical Journals, Floats In-House Publishing Plan

author: Gregory Korte, Jennifer A Dlouhy, Dana Hull
description: Billionaire Elon Musk said Wednesday that his time as formal adviser to President Donald Trump is coming to a close, raising questions about the future of the Department of Government Efficiency effort he spearheaded.
title: Musk Departs US Government With His Business Empire in Turmoil

author: Olga Kharif
description: Eric Trump told attendees at a cryptocurrency conference that he wants some big banks to “go extinct,” echoing complaints from other members of the Trump family about the traditional financial system.
title: Eric Trump Says He’d Love to See Some Big Banks ‘Go Extinct’

author: Tomoko Sato
description: Economists have slashed forecasts for growth in Malaysia and Thailand as the export-dependent economies grapple with US President Donald Trump’s global trade war.
title: Economists Cut Thai, Malaysian Growth Forecasts on Trade Turmoil
